docs.snippet: With doctors and other health care workers already on strike to protest the coup, Myanmar’s health care system may buckle under the outbreak.
docs.lead_paragraph: Three days before she was arrested by soldiers, Myanmar’s civilian leader, Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, received her first dose of a coronavirus vaccine. Her high-profile inoculation was part of a nationwide campaign to combat the virus through testing, mask-wearing, lockdowns and vaccination.

headline.main: Virus Surges in Myanmar, Where Generals Control Vaccines
headline.print_headline: Myanmar’s Covid Cases Are Soaring as Generals Control the Vaccines

docs.snippet: Shut out from mainstream medicine, some immigrants are buying expensive, unproven Covid therapies from “wellness” clinics or turning to the black market.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRESNO, Calif. — On a Tuesday afternoon in April, among tables of vegetables, clothes and telephone chargers at Fresno’s biggest outdoor flea market were prescription drugs being sold as treatments for Covid.

headline.main: Desperate for Covid Care, Undocumented Immigrants Resort to Unproven Drugs

docs.snippet: Most medical consent laws require parental permission for minors to get a vaccine. Now some places are easing restrictions for Covid shots while others are proposing new ones.
docs.lead_paragraph: Teenagers keep all sorts of secrets from their parents. Drinking. Sex. Lousy grades.

headline.main: As Parents Forbid Covid Shots, Defiant Teenagers Seek Ways to Get Them
headline.print_headline: Teens’ New Way To Defy Parents: Getting Vaccine

docs.snippet: Talk of “gain-of-function” research, a muddy category at best, brings up deep questions about how scientists should study viruses and other pathogens.
docs.lead_paragraph: At a Senate hearing on efforts to combat Covid-19 last month, Senator Rand Paul of Kentucky asked Dr. Anthony S. Fauci whether the National Institutes of Health had funded “gain-of-function” research on coronaviruses in China.

headline.main: Fight Over Covid’s Origins Renews Debate on Risks of Lab Work
headline.print_headline: Covid-19 Renews Debate About Risks of Lab Work

byline.original: By Carl Zimmer and James Gorman

docs.snippet: Production problems and a brief pause on its use kept the one-dose vaccine from becoming the game changer that health officials across the country believed it would be.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Johnson & Johnson’s single-dose coronavirus vaccine was authorized for emergency use in late February, ​it was seen as a breakthrough for reaching vulnerable and isolated Americans, a crucial alternative to vaccines that require two shots weeks apart and fussier storage. It was soon popular on college campuses, in door-to-door campaigns and with harder-to-reach communities that often struggle with access to health care.

headline.main: High Hopes for Johnson & Johnson’s Covid Vaccine Have Fizzled in the U.S.
headline.print_headline: High Hopes Fizzle for One-Dose Covid Vaccine

docs.snippet: A new $3.2 billion program will support the development of antiviral pills, which could start arriving by the end of this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: The U.S. government spent more than $18 billion last year funding drugmakers to make a Covid vaccine, an effort that led to at least five highly effective shots in record time. Now it’s pouring more than $3 billion on a neglected area of research: developing pills to fight the virus early in the course of infection, potentially saving many lives in the years to come.

headline.main: A Pill to Treat Covid-19? The U.S. Is Betting on It.
headline.print_headline: A Pill to Treat Covid-19? The U.S. Is Betting on a Few Promising Drugs.

docs.snippet: Scientists generally recommend against antibody testing after vaccination. But for some people, it makes sense.
docs.lead_paragraph: Now that tens of millions of Americans are vaccinated against the coronavirus, many are wondering: Do I have enough antibodies to keep me safe?

headline.main: Wondering if the Vaccine Worked? Get the Right Test, at the Right Time.
headline.print_headline: Antibody Test Type and Timing Key in Gauging Covid Immunity

docs.snippet: The deadly disease has sickened former coronavirus patients across the country. Doctors believe that hospitals desperate to keep Covid patients alive made choices that left them vulnerable.
docs.lead_paragraph: AHMEDABAD, India — In the stifling, tightly packed medical ward at Civil Hospital, the ear, nose and throat specialist moved briskly from one bed to the next, shining a flashlight into one patient’s mouth, examining another’s X-rays.

headline.main: In the Wake of India’s Covid Crisis, a ‘Black Fungus’ Epidemic Follows
headline.print_headline: ‘The Pandemic Has Precipitated an Epidemic’: ‘Black Fungus’ Hits India

docs.snippet: Long after some people have recovered from the virus, they find certain foods off-putting.
docs.lead_paragraph: Marcel Kuttab first sensed something was awry while brushing her teeth a year ago, several months after recovering from Covid-19.

headline.main: Distorted, Bizarre Food Smells Haunt Covid Survivors
headline.print_headline: Strange Odors and Tastes Haunt Covid Survivors

docs.snippet: An analysis of health insurance records of almost two million coronavirus patients found new issues in nearly a quarter — including those whose Covid infection was mild or asymptomatic.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hundreds of thousands of Americans have sought medical care for post-Covid health problems that they had not been diagnosed with before becoming infected with the coronavirus, according to the largest study to date of long-term symptoms in Covid-19 patients.

headline.main: Many Post-Covid Patients Are Experiencing New Medical Problems, Study Finds
headline.print_headline: After Covid, Many People Are Struck by New Ailments
